      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "278 dollars\n\nNew York Decr. 6th. 1819\n\nReceived from Jacob Harvey, Two Hundred\nand seventy eight dollars, in full for 1 Marble Tomb,\nPillar, [illegible], bottom, and letters etc.- and also for all\nexpenses attending its removal to [Shrewsbury?]\nand erecting it three over the grave of Judge\nGrimke, as pointed out to me by Dr. Allen.\n\nWilliam McKenny\n\nCopy of a letter from Dr Allen to J Harvey-\nShrewsbury December 1st 1819\n\nJacob Harvey\nDear Sir,\nI received yours [illegible] Mr McKenny, re-\nquesting me to point out the grave of Judge Grimke\nand superintend the putting up a Tomb thereon which\nwas preceded by a like request from Miss Grimke\nI have accordingly attended thereto, and so far as I am\ncapabel of judging am of opinion that he Mr\nMcKenny hath done Justice in its erection; he\nwas unfortunate in getting the bed or bottom\nstone broken on its way there, but hath put\nit together in such a manner that I do not\n\n[End page 1]\n\nthink it injured either in appearance, strength,\nor durability.\nYours etc\n[signed] - Edmund N Allen\n\n[End page 2]\n\nNew York December 6th 1819\n\nMiss Grimke's letter of 6th Nov was\nreceived on the 13th of same month, enclosing an order\non Prime Ward and Lands fo 278 dollars, which was duly\npaid.- I have now the pleasure of handing her\nMr McKenny's receipt in full for all expenses, and copy\nof a letter from Dr Allen which certifies that the\nTomb stone was properly erected.- I examined the\nInscription myself, and compared it carefully with the ori-\nfinal forwarded by Miss G. and found it to agree\nin substance, arrangement, and punctuation\n\nThe stone is a very find one, and the letters\nare well out.- On the whole, I think it\nis a creditable testimonial, and one well \nadapted for the purpose, and I trust if any of the \nfamily at a future day, should visit the spot\nthe manner in which the Tomb has been finish-\ned, will gratify their feelings.-\n\nI fear I shall not be able to visit Charles-\nton this winter, but whenever I do, it will afford\nme sincere pleasure to renew an acquaintance\nwhich, I have only to request, has been heretofore connec-\nted with any melancholy associations.-\n\nWith best wishes for Miss Grimke's happiness\nI subscribe myself respect[fully?]\nJacob Harvey\n\nMy best respects await\nMr and Misses Frazer.\n\n[End page 3]\n\n[To:] Miss Sarah M Grimke\nCharleston\nSouth Carolina\n\n[Postmarked:] New York Dec 7\n\n[End page 4]"
